Scope of the RIC Standard

The Replay Identity Capsule (RIC) defines a deterministic methodology for reconstructing the history of a sequence and converting that reconstructed past into a stable cryptographic identity.

Conceptually a sequence consists of:

(x0, T)

Where:

x0 = initial state
T = ordered sequence of transitions

Replay reconstructs the sequence trajectory:

history = [x0, x1, ..., xn]

For the demonstration kernel:

x_(i+1) = x_i + d_i

The Replay Identity Capsule is then produced as:

RIC = SHA256(encode(history))

This hash becomes the deterministic identity of the reconstructed past.


Deterministic Replay Discipline

The RIC methodology follows three deterministic rules.

Replay Identity

same sequence -> same Replay Identity Capsule

Mutation Sensitivity

changed sequence -> changed Replay Identity Capsule

Restoration Identity

restored sequence -> restored Replay Identity Capsule

These rules define deterministic replay identity.


What RIC Does NOT Do

The RIC standard does not:

• modify classical computation
• alter algorithm outputs
• introduce probabilistic inference
• perform machine learning
• inject predictive models
• simulate future behavior
• introduce randomness
• alter execution semantics

It demonstrates deterministic replay identity only.


Conformance

An implementation conforms to the RIC Standard if it:

• reconstructs sequence history deterministically
• preserves deterministic transition order
• produces stable replay identity capsules for identical sequences
• produces different capsules when sequences differ

Any implementation introducing:

• randomness
• probabilistic inference
• nondeterministic transition ordering
• hidden state mutation
• tolerance-based comparison
• adaptive runtime mutation

does not conform to the deterministic RIC standard.

Independent implementations are permitted and encouraged.


